dren":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"C:","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"https://www.lysator.liu.se/c/ten-commandments.html","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":781},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"language design","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/390016.808420","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0},{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":", ","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"http://rigaux.org/language-study/syntax-across-languages/","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":782},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"INTERCAL (and esolangs in general)","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"https://cabinetmagazine.org/issues/36/bratishenko.php","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":783},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"LISP","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"https://www.defmacro.org/ramblings/lisp.html","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":784},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"PHO","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"http://phpsadness.com/","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":785},{"children":[{"children":[{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"And it's not hard to \"prove\" it: If two people write code to solve the same problem and one makes a terrible spaghetti monster in COBOL while the other goes for super-elegant and highly abstracted solution in Haskell, does it really matter to the computer? As long as the two are compiled to the same machine code, the machine does not care. All the clever constructs used, all the elegance, they are there only to guide our intuition about the code.","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"https://250bpm.com/blog:152/index.html","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"quote","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":786},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"multiple ways to do the same thing:","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"https://hachibu.net/posts/2019/7-ways-to-loop-in-javascript/","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":787},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"A Framework for source code aesthetics","index":0}],"tag":"section","value":"","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"sec:programming-aesthetic-framework","index":0}],"tag":"label","value":"programming","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"This is where we outline a basic theory, as seen in the check-in 2.","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":788},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"What are the chronotopes of source code?","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":789},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"- local/global","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":790},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"- encapsulation/abstraction","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":791},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"- sync/async and blocking/non-blocking","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":792},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"- stack/heap","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":793},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"- memory/disk/network","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":794},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"more prosaic:","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"https://cacm.acm.org/magazines/2011/12/142527-coding-guidelines-finding-the-art-in-the-science/fulltext","index":0}],"tag":"url","value":"","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":795},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"Case studies","index":0}],"tag":"section","value":"","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"sec:case-studies","index":0}],"tag":"label","value":"programming","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"This shows the case studies.","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":796},{"children":null,"tag":"spacer","value":"","index":0},{"children":[{"children":null,"tag":"literal","value":"In conclusion, we have shown that a lot of the questions we have raised and features we have pointed out are manifested in programming languages. From there on, we have proposed our theory about levels and distances, confirming this idea of mental structures clearly manifested in source code, and of metaphors. This has been followed by case studies which have shown, in a variety of corpuses, how these are present in specific program-texts. And, again, that aesthetics is inseparable from functionality.","index":0}],"tag":"paragraph","value":"","index":797}],"tag":"include","value":"programming.tex","index":0}